# Abstract Factory Pattern — Two Implementations

---

## Implementation 1: DAOFactory (Persistence Layer)

### 1. Identified Problem

The Bank Management System has **7 DAO classes** ([AccountDAO](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/AccountDAO.java#20-169), [CustomerDAO](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/DAOFactory.java#13-14), [TransactionDAO](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/SqlServerDAOFactory.java#33-37), [TransferDAO](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/SqlServerDAOFactory.java#38-42), [LoanDAO](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/DAOFactory.java#19-20), [InterestPostingDAO](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/SqlServerDAOFactory.java#48-52), [OverdraftEventDAO](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/SqlServerDAOFactory.java#53-57)) that are instantiated directly via `new` inside **13 controller** constructors:

| Controller | Hard-coded DAO construction |
|---|---|
| [DepositHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/DepositHandler.java#18-80) | `new AccountDAO()`, `new TransactionDAO()` |
| [WithdrawCashController](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/WithdrawCashController.java#19-100) | `new AccountDAO()`, `new TransactionDAO()` |
| [TransferHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/TransferHandler.java#22-118) | `new AccountDAO()`, `new TransactionDAO()`, `new TransferDAO()` |
| [MonthlyInterestHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/MonthlyInterestHandler.java#21-110) | `new AccountDAO()`, `new TransactionDAO()`, `new InterestPostingDAO()` |
| [AuthenticationController](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/AuthenticationController.java#19-189) | `new CustomerDAO()`, `new AccountDAO()` |
| [CustomerProfileController](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/CustomerProfileController.java#12-77) | `new CustomerDAO()` |
| [AccountBalanceController](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/AccountBalanceController.java#13-68) | `new AccountDAO()` |
| [AccountStatusHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/AccountStatusHandler.java#12-62) | `new AccountDAO()` |
| [LoanApplicationHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/LoanApplicationHandler.java#12-75) | `new LoanDAO()` |
| [LoanDecisionHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/LoanDecisionHandler.java#15-63) | `new LoanDAO()` |
| [LoanStatusController](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/LoanStatusController.java#14-39) | `new LoanDAO()` |
| [TransactionHistoryController](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/TransactionHistoryController.java#19-113) | `new TransactionDAO()` |
| [OverdraftHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/OverdraftHandler.java#15-54) | `new OverdraftEventDAO()` |

This creates the following problems:

1. **Tight coupling** — every controller is directly dependent on the concrete SQL Server DAO classes. Changing the database backend would require modifying all 13 controllers.
2. **Untestable** — controllers cannot be unit-tested in isolation because they always create real database connections.
3. **Inconsistency risk** — if a controller accidentally mixes DAOs from different backends (e.g., one SQL Server DAO and one in-memory DAO), data integrity breaks. There is no mechanism to guarantee all DAOs come from the same persistence family.

### 2. Why Abstract Factory Was Selected

The **Abstract Factory** pattern solves this by providing an interface ([DAOFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/DAOFactory.java#9-25)) that defines creation methods for every DAO in the family. A concrete factory ([SqlServerDAOFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/SqlServerDAOFactory.java#11-58)) returns the matching implementation for each DAO.

**How it solves each problem:**

| Problem | Solution |
|---|---|
| **Tight coupling** | Controllers depend on the [DAOFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/DAOFactory.java#9-25) interface, not on concrete DAO classes. The factory can be swapped without touching any controller. |
| **Untestable** | An `InMemoryDAOFactory` can be injected for testing, providing stub/mock DAOs that don't require a database. |
| **Inconsistency risk** | The factory guarantees that all DAOs in the family come from the same backend — you cannot accidentally mix SQL Server and in-memory DAOs. |

**Why Abstract Factory and not other patterns?**
- **Factory Method** creates a *single* product. Here, controllers need *families* of 2-3 related DAOs that must all come from the same backend — this is exactly what Abstract Factory is designed for.
- **Singleton** already exists for [DataSourceFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/DataSourceFactory.java#16-88), but it only manages a connection pool, not the DAO creation itself.

### 3. UML Class Diagram

```mermaid
classDiagram
    direction TB

    class DAOFactory {
        <<interface>>
        +createAccountDAO() AccountDAO
        +createCustomerDAO() CustomerDAO
        +createTransactionDAO() TransactionDAO
        +createTransferDAO() TransferDAO
        +createLoanDAO() LoanDAO
        +createInterestPostingDAO() InterestPostingDAO
        +createOverdraftEventDAO() OverdraftEventDAO
    }

    class SqlServerDAOFactory {
        -INSTANCE : SqlServerDAOFactory
        -SqlServerDAOFactory()
        +getInstance()$ SqlServerDAOFactory
        +createAccountDAO() AccountDAO
        +createCustomerDAO() CustomerDAO
        +createTransactionDAO() TransactionDAO
        +createTransferDAO() TransferDAO
        +createLoanDAO() LoanDAO
        +createInterestPostingDAO() InterestPostingDAO
        +createOverdraftEventDAO() OverdraftEventDAO
    }

    class AccountDAO { }
    class CustomerDAO { }
    class TransactionDAO { }
    class TransferDAO { }
    class LoanDAO { }
    class InterestPostingDAO { }
    class OverdraftEventDAO { }

    class DepositHandler {
        +DepositHandler()
        +DepositHandler(DAOFactory)
    }
    class WithdrawCashController {
        +WithdrawCashController()
        +WithdrawCashController(DAOFactory)
    }
    class TransferHandler {
        +TransferHandler()
        +TransferHandler(DAOFactory)
    }
    class AuthenticationController {
        +AuthenticationController()
        +AuthenticationController(DAOFactory)
    }

    DAOFactory <|.. SqlServerDAOFactory : implements

    SqlServerDAOFactory ..> AccountDAO : creates
    SqlServerDAOFactory ..> CustomerDAO : creates
    SqlServerDAOFactory ..> TransactionDAO : creates
    SqlServerDAOFactory ..> TransferDAO : creates
    SqlServerDAOFactory ..> LoanDAO : creates
    SqlServerDAOFactory ..> InterestPostingDAO : creates
    SqlServerDAOFactory ..> OverdraftEventDAO : creates

    DepositHandler ..> DAOFactory : uses
    WithdrawCashController ..> DAOFactory : uses
    TransferHandler ..> DAOFactory : uses
    AuthenticationController ..> DAOFactory : uses
```

> **Reading the diagram:** The 4 representative controllers (bottom) depend on the [DAOFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/DAOFactory.java#9-25) interface (dashed `«uses»` arrows). [SqlServerDAOFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/SqlServerDAOFactory.java#11-58) implements [DAOFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/persistence/DAOFactory.java#9-25) and creates all 7 concrete DAO products. All 13 controllers follow the same pattern — only 4 are shown for readability.

---

## Implementation 2: ScreenFactory (Presentation Layer)

### 1. Identified Problem

In [BankManagementSystemApp](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#35-334), **15 presentation screens** are constructed directly with `new` across three methods:

| Method | Screens created with `new` |
|---|---|
| [start()](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#49-86) | [LoginScreen](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/LoginScreen.java#20-189), [AccountSelectionScreen](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#173-182), [AccountBalanceScreen](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#183-192), [TransactionHistoryScreen](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#193-202), [AdminDashboard](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#171-179) |
| [setupNavigationCallbacks()](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#80-154) | [CreateCustomerProfileForm](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/CreateCustomerProfileForm.java#17-115), [DepositCashForm](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/DepositCashForm.java#17-110), `WithdrawCashForm`, `UpdateAccountStatusForm`, [LoanReviewForm](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/JavaFXScreenFactory.java#54-58), `MonthlyInterestJob`, [OverdraftAlertView](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/JavaFXScreenFactory.java#64-68) |
| [createMenuBar()](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#222-283) | `TransferFundsForm`, [LoanStatusView](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/JavaFXScreenFactory.java#79-83), `ApplyForLoanForm` |
| [resetAll()](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#203-214) | All 5 core screens again |

This creates the following problems:

1. **Tight coupling** — [BankManagementSystemApp](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#35-334) imports and directly instantiates all 15 concrete screen classes. Any change to a screen constructor signature requires modifying the main app class.
2. **No UI swappability** — the application is locked to JavaFX. Switching to a different UI toolkit (e.g., Swing, web-based) would require rewriting the entire main application class.
3. **Screens form two role-based families** — admin screens ([CreateCustomerProfileForm](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/CreateCustomerProfileForm.java#17-115), [DepositCashForm](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/DepositCashForm.java#17-110), [LoanReviewForm](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/JavaFXScreenFactory.java#54-58), etc.) and customer screens (`TransferFundsForm`, `ApplyForLoanForm`, [LoanStatusView](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/JavaFXScreenFactory.java#79-83)) that must be created consistently. A factory guarantees both families are from the same toolkit.

### 2. Why Abstract Factory Was Selected

The **Abstract Factory** pattern provides a [ScreenFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/ScreenFactory.java#9-44) interface with creation methods for each screen. The concrete [JavaFXScreenFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/JavaFXScreenFactory.java#7-84) returns current JavaFX implementations.

**How it solves each problem:**

| Problem | Solution |
|---|---|
| **Tight coupling** | [BankManagementSystemApp](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#35-334) depends on [ScreenFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/ScreenFactory.java#9-44), not on 15 concrete classes. The factory can be swapped via dependency injection. |
| **No UI swappability** | A `SwingScreenFactory` or `WebScreenFactory` could be created to produce alternative screen implementations without modifying [BankManagementSystemApp](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#35-334). |
| **Inconsistent families** | The factory guarantees all screens come from the same UI toolkit — you cannot accidentally mix JavaFX and Swing screens. |

**Why Abstract Factory and not other patterns?**
- **Factory Method** creates a single product. The main application needs *families* of related screens (admin + customer), all from the same toolkit.
- **Builder** is for constructing complex objects step-by-step. Screens are created fully-formed in a single step.

### 3. UML Class Diagram

```mermaid
classDiagram
    direction TB

    class ScreenFactory {
        <<interface>>
        +createLoginScreen() LoginScreen
        +createAccountSelectionScreen() AccountSelectionScreen
        +createAccountBalanceScreen() AccountBalanceScreen
        +createTransactionHistoryScreen() TransactionHistoryScreen
        +createAdminDashboard() AdminDashboard
        +createCustomerProfileForm() CreateCustomerProfileForm
        +createDepositForm() DepositCashForm
        +createWithdrawForm() WithdrawCashForm
        +createAccountStatusForm() UpdateAccountStatusForm
        +createLoanReviewForm() LoanReviewForm
        +createInterestJobScreen() MonthlyInterestJob
        +createOverdraftAlertView() OverdraftAlertView
        +createTransferForm() TransferFundsForm
        +createLoanApplicationForm() ApplyForLoanForm
        +createLoanStatusView() LoanStatusView
    }

    class JavaFXScreenFactory {
        +createLoginScreen() LoginScreen
        +createAccountSelectionScreen() AccountSelectionScreen
        +createAccountBalanceScreen() AccountBalanceScreen
        +createTransactionHistoryScreen() TransactionHistoryScreen
        +createAdminDashboard() AdminDashboard
        +createCustomerProfileForm() CreateCustomerProfileForm
        +createDepositForm() DepositCashForm
        +createWithdrawForm() WithdrawCashForm
        +createAccountStatusForm() UpdateAccountStatusForm
        +createLoanReviewForm() LoanReviewForm
        +createInterestJobScreen() MonthlyInterestJob
        +createOverdraftAlertView() OverdraftAlertView
        +createTransferForm() TransferFundsForm
        +createLoanApplicationForm() ApplyForLoanForm
        +createLoanStatusView() LoanStatusView
    }

    class LoginScreen { }
    class AccountSelectionScreen { }
    class AccountBalanceScreen { }
    class AdminDashboard { }
    class DepositCashForm { }
    class WithdrawCashForm { }
    class TransferFundsForm { }
    class LoanReviewForm { }
    class ApplyForLoanForm { }
    class LoanStatusView { }

    class BankManagementSystemApp {
        -screenFactory : ScreenFactory
        +start(Stage)
        -setupNavigationCallbacks()
        -resetAll()
    }

    ScreenFactory <|.. JavaFXScreenFactory : implements

    JavaFXScreenFactory ..> LoginScreen : creates
    JavaFXScreenFactory ..> AccountSelectionScreen : creates
    JavaFXScreenFactory ..> AccountBalanceScreen : creates
    JavaFXScreenFactory ..> AdminDashboard : creates
    JavaFXScreenFactory ..> DepositCashForm : creates
    JavaFXScreenFactory ..> WithdrawCashForm : creates
    JavaFXScreenFactory ..> TransferFundsForm : creates
    JavaFXScreenFactory ..> LoanReviewForm : creates
    JavaFXScreenFactory ..> ApplyForLoanForm : creates
    JavaFXScreenFactory ..> LoanStatusView : creates

    BankManagementSystemApp ..> ScreenFactory : uses
```

> **Reading the diagram:** [BankManagementSystemApp](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/BankManagementSystemApp.java#35-334) depends only on the [ScreenFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/ScreenFactory.java#9-44) interface (dashed `«uses»` arrow). [JavaFXScreenFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/JavaFXScreenFactory.java#7-84) implements the interface and creates all 15 concrete screen products (10 shown for readability). Swapping [JavaFXScreenFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/presentation/JavaFXScreenFactory.java#7-84) for a different implementation changes the entire UI without touching the application class.
